article.description:
Gary Payton collected 21 points, six 
rebounds and six assists as the Seattle SuperSonics defeated the
injury-ravaged Toronto Raptors, 91-79.
article.headline: Raps' effort there but not key players in loss to Sonics
article.linkText: Shorthanded Raptors can't keep pace with Sonics
article.story:
TORONTO (AP) -- Without their three best players, the Toronto Raptors just couldn't match up with the Seattle SuperSonics.
Payton

Gary Payton scored 21 points as the SuperSonics beat the injury-riddled Raptors 91-79 Friday night for their second straight road victory. The Raptors, who have lost three straight and five of six, were missing injured All-Star Vince Carter, leading rebounder Antonio Davis and point guard Alvin Williams. "We put the effort out, but we just don't have enough guys,'' Carter said. Lindsey Hunter had a team-high 21 for the Raptors, who are also missing Lamond Murray, Eric Montross and Mamadou N'diaye. Toronto has used 11 starting lineups in 22 games this season. "They played a solid game without a lot of key guys. We were able to control the game for the most part, but I thought they gave a legit effort,'' Seattle coach Nate McMillan said. Vladimir Radmanovic added 15 points and Desmond Mason had 14 for the SuperSonics, who won consecutive games for the first time since Nov. 17. "Nobody is going to feel sympathy for nobody,'' said Payton, who also had six assists and six rebounds. "If you come out here and play, we are going to try to get a win.'' After Payton's 3-pointer gave Seattle an 11-point lead with 4:13 left, Hunter made consecutive 3-pointers. His free throw cut the deficit to seven with 3:12 remaining. Payton followed with a fadeaway jumper, and Toronto's final points of the game came on Jelani McCoy's layup with 2:16 left. "We just couldn't get it done, but our guys tried,'' Toronto coach Lenny Wilkens said. Rashard Lewis and Predrag Drobnjak each added 12 points for the SuperSonics, whose five-game road trip continues with games against Detroit on Saturday and Cleveland on Monday. Payton had 10 points and Mason, Drobnjak and Radmanovic each had eight as Seattle led 42-35 at halftime. Payton's hook shot gave Seattle a 13-point lead late in the third quarter, but Hunter kept the Raptors close in the fourth.

Game notes
The Raptors started Jermaine Jackson, Lenard, Greg Foster, Jerome Williams and Morris Peterson. ... Carter (straight right knee) isn't expected back for at least a week and a half. Davis (swollen right knee) and Alvin Williams (sore left ankle) are day-to-day. Murray (ligament tear in his foot) is expected to return in March. ... The SuperSonics are 8-6 on the road. ... Williams, averaging 16.2 points and 5.2 assists, was injured against Dallas on Dec. 2 and aggravated his ankle in the second quarter of Wednesday's 96-83 loss at Cleveland.
